Here are the public test cases for feature1_set_and_read:
{
  "description": "The store is an observable object. Assigning a value to a top-level property records the property's value so it can later be read back through the same object, and reading a property returns the most recently assigned value. Each assignment is also reported to any registered change subscriber as the path of the property that changed. The adapter prints each requested read, the ordered list of reported change paths, and a final snapshot of the whole store.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {},
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "count"
            ],
            "value": 1
          },
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "name"
            ],
            "value": "ada"
          },
          {
            "op": "get",
            "path": [
              "count"
            ]
          },
          {
            "op": "get",
            "path": [
              "name"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "get store.count = 1\nget store.name = \"ada\"\nchanges=[\"store.count\",\"store.name\"]\nsnapshot={\"count\":1,\"name\":\"ada\"}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature2_nested_update:
{
  "description": "Assignments may target a property nested several levels deep inside the store. Writing to a deep property updates only that property, leaving the rest of the surrounding structure intact, and the new value is observable when the nested location is read back. A deep write may either overwrite an existing nested property or introduce a new property alongside existing siblings. The reported change path identifies the exact nested location that changed, from the root down to the written property.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "user": {
            "name": "ada",
            "address": {
              "city": "london"
            }
          }
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "user",
              "address",
              "city"
            ],
            "value": "paris"
          },
          {
            "op": "get",
            "path": [
              "user",
              "address",
              "city"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "get store.user.address.city = \"paris\"\nchanges=[\"store.user.address.city\"]\nsnapshot={\"user\":{\"address\":{\"city\":\"paris\"},\"name\":\"ada\"}}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature3_delete:
{
  "description": "A property can be removed from the store entirely, whether it sits at the top level or nested inside another object. After removal the property is absent from the store snapshot while all other properties remain. Removal of a property is reported to the change subscriber as the path of the property that was removed.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "a": 1,
          "b": 2
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "delete",
            "path": [
              "a"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "changes=[\"store.a\"]\nsnapshot={\"b\":2}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature4_structural_sharing:
{
  "description": "Updates apply structural sharing: when a nested property changes, only the objects along the path from the root to the changed property are rebuilt, while every object not on that path keeps its original reference. An identity probe captures the reference at a location before the mutation and compares it with the reference at the same location afterwards; it reports the location as preserved when the reference is unchanged and replaced when it was rebuilt. Objects on the changed path (the changed node's ancestors) are reported as replaced, and untouched sibling sub-trees are reported as preserved.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "a": {
            "x": 1
          },
          "b": {
            "y": 2
          },
          "list": [
            1,
            2
          ]
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "a",
              "x"
            ],
            "value": 99
          }
        ],
        "identity": [
          [
            "a"
          ],
          [
            "b"
          ],
          [
            "list"
          ]
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "changes=[\"store.a.x\"]\nidentity store.a = replaced\nidentity store.b = preserved\nidentity store.list = preserved\nsnapshot={\"a\":{\"x\":99},\"b\":{\"y\":2},\"list\":[1,2]}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature5_array_operations:
{
  "description": "Arrays held in the store are observable in the same way as objects. Assigning to an existing index replaces that element; assigning to the index one past the end appends a new element and grows the array's length accordingly. Elements that are themselves objects participate in structural sharing, so changing one element's property leaves the other elements' references untouched. A change to an element is reported with a path whose final segment is the element's index, and the array contents are observable in order through reads and the snapshot.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "items": [
            10,
            20,
            30
          ]
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "items",
              1
            ],
            "value": 99
          },
          {
            "op": "get",
            "path": [
              "items"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "get store.items = [10,99,30]\nchanges=[\"store.items.1\"]\nsnapshot={\"items\":[10,99,30]}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature6_change_notification_order:
{
  "description": "Every mutation that flows through the store is reported to the change subscriber in the exact order the mutations are applied. Repeated changes to the same property each produce their own report rather than being collapsed, and a mix of assignments and removals is reported in interleaved order. The change subscriber receives one entry per mutation, each entry being the path of the affected property.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "a": 0,
          "b": 0,
          "c": 0
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "b"
            ],
            "value": 2
          },
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "a"
            ],
            "value": 1
          },
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "c"
            ],
            "value": 3
          },
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "a"
            ],
            "value": 9
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "changes=[\"store.b\",\"store.a\",\"store.c\",\"store.a\"]\nsnapshot={\"a\":9,\"b\":2,\"c\":3}\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature7_invalid_path_handling:
{
  "description": "Operations that require navigating through a non-existent or non-navigable location are rejected. Attempting to assign into a property whose parent object does not exist, or attempting to read a property of a primitive value as though it were an object, does not produce store contents; instead the adapter reports a single neutral error category indicating the path could not be resolved.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "a": 1
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "set",
            "path": [
              "missing",
              "deep"
            ],
            "value": 1
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "error=invalid_path\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the public test cases for feature8_replace_store:
{
  "description": "The entire store can be replaced wholesale with a new set of contents while keeping the same store object identity. Replacing first removes every property currently present and then installs the properties of the replacement, so previously present keys disappear and the new keys become readable. Both the removals of the old properties and the additions of the new ones are reported to the change subscriber, removals first and additions after.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "init": {
          "old1": 1,
          "old2": 2
        },
        "ops": [
          {
            "op": "replace",
            "value": {
              "new1": 10,
              "new2": 20
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "changes=[\"store.old1\",\"store.old2\",\"store.new1\",\"store.new2\"]\nsnapshot={\"new1\":10,\"new2\":20}\n"
    }
  ]
}
